revision.text:
{{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = {{PAGENAME}} | synonyms = | image = | width = | alt = | caption = | pronounce = | field = | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }} '''Avellis syndrome''' is a [[neurological disorder]] characterized by a peculiar form of alternating [[paralysis]]. There is paralysis of the [[soft palate]] and [[vocal cords]] on one side and loss of [[pain sensation]] and [[temperature sense]] on the other side, including the extremities, trunk, and neck. It usually results from [[Vascular occlusion|occlusion]] of the [[vertebral artery]] in [[lesion]]s of the [[nucleus ambiguous]] and [[pyramidal tract]]. [[Horner's syndrome]] may be associated. In the original description, the [[Vagus nerve|vagus]] and [[glossopharyngeal nerve]]s were involved; concomitant involvement of the neighbouring [[cranial nerve]]s was observed later.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Avellis' Syndrome in Brainstem Infarctions | work = Fortsch. Neurol. Psychiatr. | date = Dec 2003 | pmid=14661158 | doi=10.1055/s-2003-45345 | volume=71 | pages=650-3 | last1 = Krasnianski | first1 = M | last2 = Neudecker | first2 = S | last3 = Schlüter | first3 = A | last4 = Zierz | first4 = S}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Avellis Syndrome | work = | publisher =whonamedit | date = | url = http://www.whonamedit.com/synd.cfm/314.html | doi = | accessdate = 10 Mar 2013}}</ref>
