{{Orphan|date=March 2016}}
The '''Four Cornerstone Model of Emotional Intelligence''' is based on [[emotional literacy]], emotional fitness, emotional depth, and [[emotional alchemy]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title = Emotional Intelligence and Leadership Style: An Investigation Within a Major Telecommunications Company|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=_sxc9ShLvL4C|publisher = ProQuest|date = 2007-01-01|isbn = 9780549319085|language = en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url = http://www.training-games.com/pdf/Connecting-Emotional-Intell-To-Success_pdf.pdf|title = Connecting Emotional Intelligence to Success in the Workplace|last = A. Kerr|first = Barbara|date = 2009|journal = |doi = |pmid = |access-date = |publisher = HRDQ}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Models of emotional intelligence: Similarities and discrepancies|url = http://www.myresearchjournals.com/index.php/IJPP/article/view/4430|journal = Indian Journal of Positive Psychology|date = 2015-08-10|issn = 2229-4937|volume = 6|issue = 2|language = en|first = Soni|last = Kewalramani|first2 = Manju|last2 = Agrawal|first3 = Mukta Rani|last3 = Rastogi}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|title = Emotional Intelligence and Burnout among Teachers in a Rural Florida School District|url = http://ufdc.ufl.edu/UFE0042690/00001|website = ufdc.ufl.edu|accessdate = 2015-09-23}}</ref><ref name=":3">{{Cite book|title = Executive EQ: Emotional Intelligence in Leadership and Organizations|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=k9jNwaVUFoQC|publisher = Penguin|date = 1998-01-01|isbn = 9780399524042|language = en|first = Robert K.|last = Cooper|first2 = Ayman|last2 = Sawaf}}</ref> The model moves [[emotional intelligence]] out of the realm of psychological analysis and philosophical theories and instead focuses on knowledge, exploration and practical application.<ref name=GeneralTeachingCompetency>{{cite journal|author1=Venkoba Narayanappa|title=A Study of General Teaching Competency of Women Student Teachers in Relation to their Interest in Teaching, Emotional Intelligence, Adjustment and Personality|url=http://anubooks.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/17-A-Study-of-General-Teaching-Competency-of-Women-Student-Teachers-in-Relation-to-their-Interest-in-Teaching-Emotional-Intelligence-Adjustment-and-Personality.pdf|accessdate=23 September 2015|publisher=Karnataka State women University, Bijapur}}</ref>
== Concept == The Four cornerstone model was developed by [[Ayman Sawaf]] and Robert Cooper in 1997.<ref name=":3" /><ref name=":2">{{Cite journal|title = Emotional Intelligence at the Workplace: A preliminary study of male executives in the Public and Private sector organisations|url = http://econpapers.repec.org/paper/iimiimawp/wp01736.htm|first = Kaushal|last = Geetika|first2 = Dholakia|last2 = Jigisha}}</ref> Multiple studies and research carried out in regards to emotional intelligence based on this model revealed a marginal qualitative difference between the public and private sector executives and expand on the usage of this model.<ref name=":2" /> The concept focuses on the fact that creative involvement in a stimulating job, opportunity, or an exciting discussion results in an increase in alertness, emotional energy, and performance. Repetitive and boring tasks on the other hand put the performer in danger of dismay, lack of efficiency and making mistakes. This generates its explanation from the fact that professionalism is based on self-discipline, inner guidance and emotional drive.<ref name=":3" /><ref>{{Cite journal|url = https://ujdigispace.uj.ac.za/bitstream/handle/10210/5556/E.M.%20VERMEULEN_2001_MA.pdf|title = EMOTIONAL INTELLIGENCE AS DETERMINANTOF THE IDEAL CHARACTERISTICS TO DELIVER THE BEST SERVICE TO CUSTOMERS|last = MARIA VERMEULEN|first = ELIZABETH|date = August 2001|journal = |doi = |pmid = |access-date = |publisher = UNIVERSITY OF WALES}}</ref>
=== The Four Factors === The four cornerstone model is mixed model of [[emotional intelligence]] based on four factors labeled as cornerstones:<ref name=":3" /><ref>{{Cite web|title = Pre-Doctoral Graduate Personal Emotional Intelligence Assessment - Sumo Nova|url = http://sumonova.com/pre-doctoral-graduate-personal-emotional-intelligence-assessment/|website = sumonova.com|accessdate = 2015-09-23}}</ref><ref name=Aarhat>{{cite journal|author1=Aneesh Kurian|title=Adolescents And Emotional Intelligence: A Critical Analysis|journal=Aarhat Multidisciplinary International Education Research Journal|date=2013|volume=2|issue=5|url=http://amierj.weebly.com/uploads/1/0/8/0/10800505/ak3.pdf|accessdate=23 September 2015|issn=2278-5655}}</ref> # Emotional literacy – the ability to identify, respect, and express feelings appropriately. This may include practical intuition, emotional honesty, emotional energy and emotional feedback.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /> # Emotional fitness – consists of trust resilience, authenticity and renewal.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /> # Emotional depth – involves applying integrity and core values in influencing others without manipulation or control.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /> # Emotional alchemy – blending and tuning emotions to find opportunities and realization of such opportunities by creativity, cognitive thinking and rhetoric.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" />
